Thousands of mourners attended the Wednesday burial of Mombasa billionaire Tahir Sheikh Said, whose death marked the end of an era.The prominent billionaire, known for TSS bus services and other businesses, died on Tuesday at Milpark hospital in South Africa. His son Tahir Mohamed said he had been sick for a while.[VIDEO] Mombasa tycoon Tahir Sheikh Said dies at South Africa hospitalSaid's body arrived early on Wednesday and was taken to his family home in Kizingo area.He was buried at Kikowani Muslim Cemetery where leaders including Sheriff Nassir Abdallah Taib were laid to rest.Former Chief Kadhi Sheikh Hammad Kassim led the mourners in the final prayers, conducted at TSS mosque along Haile Selassie Avenue before the burial.Among those who attended the burial were Mombasa Senator Hassan Omar, politicians Suleiman Shahbal and Anania Mwaboza, and Mombasa Governor Hassan Joho's elder brother Joho Abubakar, popularly known as Abu.The leaders eulogised Said as an icon whose death they said was a big blow to the society that depended on him. They said he was generous and helped the less fortunate people in the region.Tahir was also in the real estate and milling businesses, and had ventures at the Coast and other parts of the country.The billionaire's sons were recently involved in a fight for the control of his empire.Sabir Tahir Said and his younger brother Sheikh Noorein Twahir want control of the transport segment of two firms - Transmara Logistics and TSS Pop Service Stations.The businessman's family has been involved in wrangles over loan defaults of about Sh2.7 billion, associated with TSS Unga Millers.Early in 2015, the government cancelled title deeds to large tracts of land in Lamu county that were associated with the tycoon.Some of the land is said to have been used to secure loans in excess of Sh5 billion from two banks that are listed on the stock exchange.